{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689895/1957101401/0450.xml":{"full_text":"THI KEY WEST CITIZEN Monday, October 14, 1957\nPage 6\nTlx Key West Citizen\nPublished daily (except Sunday) from Ihe Citizen BuHding.\ncorner of Greene and Ann Streets\nEntered at Ke: West, Fionas, as Second Class Matter\nL P ARTMAN. Editor and Publisher, 1913-1934\nNOFMAN D. ARTMAN, Editor and CLAY RILEY Advertising Maoaaor\nPublisher RAYFORD ROBERTS, Circulation\nMARGARET FORESMAN, City Editor manager\nPERCY CURRY Mechanical Superintendent\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES NATIONAL ADVERTISING REPRESENTS\n(By Carrier) TIVES: theis I Simpson Co., tnc., I t\nMtb St., New York 82, N Y\n1 Year MEMBER OF CHE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nMonths 6.60 The Associated Press is entitled exclusively\n8 Months 390 to the use for reputUcation of all the local\n1 Month 1.18 news printed in this newspaper as well as all\nA P news dispatches.\nTELEPHONE CY \u00ab-SMI\nShould Shoreline Building\nRules Be Tightened?\nUp in Miami Beach, building operations last week\nunearthed two old groins\u2014man-made dikes of wood and\nsteel designed to catch sand and create land beyond the\nnatural shoreline.\nThe discovery of these groins threw the ownership\nof the property and the 20-million-dollar Carillon Hotel\ninto dispute after city records showed the property,\nwhich was about 220 feet deep in 1927, \u201cgrew\u201d to 330\nfeet deep by 1955. The obvious accusation would be\nthat the property owners filled some ocean bottom to\nadd to their land without ever buying the new ground\nfrom the State of Florida.\nWe doubt the dispute will amount to much.\nIt would cost some people too much money.\nAs the Miami Beach city attorney pointed out, land\ngained by groins usually belongs to the \"upland owner.\"\nAnd many other Miami Beach hotels may have used the\nsame tactics to get extra land.\nOcean bottom, generally, is in the hands of the Flor\nida Internal Improvement Fund, run by a board of trus\ntees appointed by the governor. They have the right\nto sell this land if they see fit\u2014and they sell chunks of\nit quite often.\nThe only thing, apparently, that stops this board\nfrom selling land is a possible threat either to boat navi\ngation or a waterfront property owner\u2019s view. Usually,\nanybody who owns property down to the shoreline is\ngiven first call on buying underwater land in front of\nhim.\nThat\u2019s all right\u2014so far as it goes.\nBut we wonder if it hasn't gone too far.\nIn many, many cases all over Florida\u2014and in a\ncouple of cases in Key West\u2014property owners have\nused this \u201cfirst call\u201d privilege to build out into the water\nand cut off strips of beach that might have added a\ngreat deal to the open, attractive looks of the neigh\nborhood if they\u2019d been left untouched. And we think\nit might be a good idea if some law were passed to bar\nmotels, hotels and other land-owners in residential neigh\nborhoods from swallowing up the natural sand beach\nunder tons of steel and concrete.\nWe realize that many industries must build out\nover the shoreline. Steamship lines, fish houses and the\nlike must dock boats in deep water. And in some cases,\n'where the beach front is swampy, rocky and overgrown\nby mangroves, and it isn\u2019t used by the public anyway,\nthere\u2019s probably no harm in building on it.\nBut all across Florida, thousands of tourists and\nresidents, too. are finding it harder and harder to find\na long stretch of sandy public beach on which to walk,\nlook for shells, swim, land a small boat or just to wan\nder around. Tourists and residents, too. like such a\natretch of beach. And many hotels and clubs along the\nwaterfront have fenced in wide sections of public beach\nso that only their guests or members can use them.\nWe think this is wrong and we'd like to see it\nstopped. Many a lake, beach and swimming hole,\nacross the nation, has been ruined by fences, building\nadditions and \u201cprivate\u2014members only\u201d signs.\nScattered History\nThe historian of today\u2019s America must do some jump\ning around the country. Besides the Library of Congress\nof Congress at Washington, and the large university\nand public libraries, he must consult also the Frank\nlin Roosevelt documents at Hyde Park. N. Y., the Tru\nman papers at Independence. Mo., and the Eisenhower\nlibrary at Abilene, Kansas. To these have now been\nadded the materials in the Sam Rayburn memorial\nlibrary at Nonham, Tex., whose dedication is schedul\ned for Oct. 9.\nRayburn has been speaker of the house for 13 years,\n-longer than any other man. He has been in Congress\nfor 45 years, one of the longest services on record.\nHe began in 1948 to collect the letters, books and papers\nthat make up the library. Private donations have paid\nmost of the cost.\nThis dispersion of historical materials has the mer\nit of preventing the loss of priceless items which con\ncentration might bring about in war. Yet it is hard on\na busy, impoverished historian who has to round up\nwidely separated documents. Fortunately there is a\n.solution: microfilming. All the presidential libraries\nAdW housed separately should be microfilmed, thus\nmaking their contents widely available.\nPoint Of View\nIt is now possible, in the United States of Ameri\nca, for a fond dog owner to buy his pet a mink coat.\nPrices start at around $250.\nFor those who don't care to spend that kind of\nrrroney but want to deck out a favorite pooch in styl\nish garb, there are such items as these. A black lace\ncocktail collar with matching cocktail apron for the\ndog s mistress, a terry cloth beach robe; a garbardine\nraincoat with hood and matching leggings; a jewel\ned collar to match a jeweled choker for miladv.\nAmericans spend about 25 million dollars a year\non leashes, pet harnesses, and such items as those men\nrioned above. It s all cute as can be\u2014unless one happens\nto look at it through the eyes of those millions on earth\nwho worry more about where their next meal is coming\nfrom than about whether their dogs have cocktail\ncollars.\nBUT IS HE HEADED FOR THE RIGHT GOAL!\n\n\u201c5'\n\n\nI, py A\n\u2014y\nPEOPLE\u2019S EORUM\nThe Citizen welcomes expression: of the views of its read\ners, but the editor reserves the right to delete any items which\nare considered libelous or unwarranted. The writers should be\nfair and confine the letters to 200 words and write on one side\nof the paper only. Signature of the writer must accompany the\nletters and will be published unless requested otherwise.\nABOUT THE SEWERS\nEditor, The Citizen:\nReferring to the recent report\nof engineers Smith and Gillespie\non the operation of our sewer\nsystem.\nFor the information of those\nthat have not seen the report, it\nshows an increase of $16,864 for\nthe year 1956 over 1955, an in\ncrease of ,15-plus per cent, quite an\nincrease. There was an increase\nof $8,558 for 1957 over 1956, an in\ncrease of .09-plus per cent, also a\nhigh increase. What will the in\ncrease be for 1958 over 1957?\nIt would be interesting to hear\nwhat, if anything, the City ad-\nToday\u2019s Business Mirror\nNEW YORK UH\u2014A 100 mfll.on\ndollar a day prop to business may\nget a little shaky next year. This\nis the average amount business it\nself has been putting back into\nthe economy each day of this year\nin its spending for plant and\nequipment-\nContract awards for factory\nconstruction are declining. Cor\nporate directors are appropriating\nfar less money now for new capi\ntal spending than they were a\nyear ago.\nOne survey just made by the\nResearch Institute of America\nindicates spending next year could\ndrop seven billion dollars below\nthis year s record 37 billion dol\nlars. Other surveys look for only\na two billion dollar drop in an\nnual rate in the early months of\n1958.\nReasons given: Uncertainty\nover the business outlook: the\ncapacity to produce already in ex\ncess of demand for the time\nbefng: and the natural comple\ntion of big programs started some\ntime back.\nA survey by the Department of\nCommerce and the Securities and\nExchange Commission shows th?\nexpansion boom leveling off now\nand dropping slightly by the end\nof the year.\nThe expected total this year of\n37 billion dollars would be 6.5 per\ncent over the 35 bfilion spent last\nyear, which was a whopping 22 .5\nper cent over spending in 1955.\nSpending less this year than last\nwere auto, textile and stone, clay\nCrossword Puzzle\n32. Long way\n33. Chalice\n34. Solemn\n35. Philippine\nnegrito\n36. Secure\n37. Lapel\n38. Wager\n39. Alternative\n40. Determine\n42. Achieve\n43. Seed cov\nering\n45. Corrode\n47. Cease\n48. Luzon\nsavage\n51. Cleansing\nmaterial\n54. Not cold\n55 Adminis\ntrator\n57. Sooner than\n58 Food\n59. Support\nACROSS\n1. Soft food\n4. Medical\nfluid\n9. Climbing\nJ vine\n12. Lack of\ncapacity\n14. Finial on\na pagoda\n15. Smoking\ndevice\n19. Adversary\n17. Dispatched\n18. Limb\n20. Hoarfrost\n21. At home\n23. Male turkey\n27. Singing\nsyllable\n29. Large\ndrinking\nt vessel\n31. Nostrils\n\nministration proposes to do to\nstop these high percentage of in\ncreases. Laymen can see no rea\nson for such increases. There is\nexpected to be small increases\nto cover the cost of power as\nthe load increases due to addi\ntional sewer connections.\nWhile on this subject 1 would\nlike to call to the attention of\nthe administration the fact that\nthere is yet a number of resi\ndences that have not connected\nup to the sewer, yet you see\nsome of the property owners rid\ning around expensive cars.\nSincerely,\nTJK\nBy SAM DAWSON\nand glass produet companies.\nPublic utilities are expected to\nkeep up their expansion plans re\ngardless of the general business\ntrend. This year they're spending\n6U billion dollars, compared witn\n4 billion last year.\nThe Institute's survey found 19\nper cent of the 1.000 companies\npolled planning to increase spend\ning and 35 per cent foreseeing no\nchange.\nBovs I nearth\nBuried Grenade\nKANSAS CITY P Billy and\nMickey Donahue charged into\nthe?r home, their faces aglow wiht\nexcitement.\n\"Goody, goody.\u201d they yelled\n\"We found a hand grenade.\u201d\nThe boys' stepfather, Robert\nTerranova, grabbed the grenade\nand gingerly put it in a corner\nwhile Mrs. Terranova telephoned\nthe police.\nBill. 8. and Mickey,, 10. found\nthe grenade while digging in a\nvacant lot with a claw hammer.\n\"I thought it was a rock,\u201d said\nMickey, and I hit it a couple of\ntimes with the hammer. After I\npulled it out of the hole I knew\nwhat it was because I've seen\nhand grenades on television.\u201d\nFormer lightweight boxing\nchampion Lew Jenkins plans to\nmake the Army his career. He is\na master sergeant.\nSolution of Yootor^ay'a Fwnio\nDOWN\n1. Small seed\n2 Keel-billed\ncuckoo\n3. Father\n4. Silicon\nsymbol\n5. Sprite\n6. River: Sp.\n7. Shoshonean\nIndian\nOverthrow Of Government Is\nOld Stuff To Thailand People\nBy MURRAY FROMSON\nl BANGKOK P\u2014 The people of\nThaXand have accepted their\nlatest government change just\nabout as casually as they nould\na fresh bowl of rice.\nIn this Asian kingdom the coup\nd\u2019etat is an accepted way of life.\nLast month s overthrow of Field\nMarshal Pibulsonggram was the\nfifth major coup since 1932. The\nI new strong man is Field Marshal\nSarit Thanarat.\nPersonal loyalties, widely ac\ncepted in the West, are laughed\nat in Thailand. In fact, the people\ndon't even understand the terms.\ni They were puzzled when the new\ni rulers promised they would hold\nhonest elections in December,\nchange the structure of the hated\npolice force and curb corruption.\nThe Thais recall an old proverb\nthat you can't replace a full lion\nwith an empty tiger.\u201d Now- they\nask how Sar.\u2019t intends to keep his\nsupporters happy without offering\nthem the same lucrative benefits\ntheir predecessors got.\nEven so. the Thais seem happy\nover the removal of Pibul and po\nlice general Shao Sryianonda. The\nWest liked Pibul but at home he\nwas unpopular.\n\".Yame a dictator who was ever\npopular,\u201d one Thai commented.\nPhao, whose interests supposed\nly deluded the running of opium\nto other southeast Asian coun\ntries. was unquestionably Thai\nland's most unpopular man.\nThais who associated with West\nerners felt the coercion and illegal\nmethods he used in last Febru\nary's elections brought discredit\nto the country.\nThe election, combined with a\nsmouldering hatred for the touch\npolice, was one of the last big\nnails driven into Pibuls political\ncoffin.\nPibul made a mistake by de\nfending Phao once too often. Sa\nrft, junior member of the Pibul-\nPhao-Sarit trio that ruled for 10\nyears, recognized growing dis\ncontent and reasoned that an at\ntack on Pibul and Paho was an\nattack on him as well.\nKey West\nIn Days Gone By\nOct. 14, 1937\nMiss Blanche Brantley was\nawarded the prize of a bridge\nlamp at this morning's session\nof the theater party given by the\nKey West Electric Co. at the\nMonroe Theater.\nMonroe County delinquent taxes\non the Colonial Hotel were paid\nthis morning. Tax Collector Ladd\nsaid the money amounted to 55,-\n008,50.\n\nOct. 14, 1947\nTwo and a quarter millions of\ndollars will be spent in Dadi\nand Broward Counties for relief\nwork as a result of floods caused\nby heavy rams, the Red Cross\nsaid today.\nCharles S. Taylor today an\nnounced as a candidate for city\ncommissioner. Taylor was one of\nhe men who drew up the ori\nginal city charter.\nLEARN TO SEW\nCDCC\niKll wW\nLESSONS\nPLAIN STITCH\nING\nZIG-ZAG\nFANCY SEWING\nBUTTON HOLES\nEMBROIDERY\nMONOGRAMS\nFor Information CALL 4-1241\nSewing Machine\nExchange\n826 DUVAL STREET\n\"We Repair All Makes\"\n8 Possesstre\npronoun\n9 Account\nentry\n10. Revered\n11 However\n13. Masa of ice\n17. Title\n19. Animal of\nmixed breed\n20 Withhold\n21. Adult insect\n22. Upper part\nof a fraction\n24. Exposes\n25. Well done\n26. Flat\n28. Muse of\npoetry\n30. Channel to\ninland\n32. Little he\n40 Tear\n41. Where the\nsun rises\n44. Repetition\n46. Labor\n47. That woman\n48. Chopping\ninstrument\n49. Supper\n50. Part of a\nPI\u00bbF\n52. Salutation\n53. Wooden pin\n55. Type square\n56. Pronoun\na NO MATTER WHAT YOUR PLANS\nv\u00ab fe\u00bb\n^CASH\n$25 to $6OO\nMoney for any worthy\npurpose on Signature\nonly, cor or furniture\nClifton R. McNabb, Manager\n524 Southard St CY. 6-5681, Key West\nHours: Mon.-Frx 9-5; Sat. 8:30-12 Open evenings by appointment\nLoons mode Ie rosido\u00dfH of aeorby \u00bbowb\u00bb\nRather than risk his own com\nmercial interests, Sant turned on\nhis old cronies.\nThe new boss K a hard-headed,\nsuccessful businessman who rec\nognizes 140 million in I'S. assist\nance received here since 1951 has\nbeen a stimulus to his own eco\nnomic pursuits. He also has a\nclose association w^h Chinese\nmerchants who lobby tor extend\ned trade with Red China.\nT!\u00bbe most apt description of\nSarit is probably that he is pro-\nSarit. His interest in politi<cs ap\npears to depend entirely on what\neffect it will have on his commer-l\ncial firms, which have a wide\nrange. In this Sarft is acting much\nlike any other Thai. The coun\ntry s approach to foreign policy is\nnot fundamentally tempered by\nmoral or ideological considera\ntions. It is a policy of fence-sitting\nself-Fnterest which the Thais have\nemployed effectively for more\nthan a century to remain free ot\nforeign domination.\nPolitical\nAnnouncements\nMUNICIPAL ELECTION,\nNOVEMBER 5, 1957\nFor Mayor\n(group\u2019d\nLuigi celluci\nFor Mayor\n(group\u2019 1)\nDR. DELIO COBO\nb or Mayor\n(GROUP* 1)\nC. B. HARVEY\n(Re-Elect)\nLor City Commissioner\nBILL G. CHAPPELL\n(Re- Elect)\n(GROUP 2)\nL'or City Commissioner\n(GROUP 2)\nHARRY F. KNIGHT\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 3)\nLOUIS CARBONELL\n(Re-Elect)\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 3)\nJACK E. CLARKE\nL'or City Commissioner\n(GROUP 3)\nLOUIS M. J. EISNER\nL'or (Jty Commissioner\n(GROUP 3)\nARTHUR MULBERG\nFor (Jty Commissioner\n(GROUP 3)\nJ. IL Cowboy\u2019 WATSON\nL'or Citv Commissioner\n(GROUP 4)\nJACK C. DELANEY\n(Ra-Elect)\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 4)\nC HARLES PARRA\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 4)\nAUSTIN ROBERTS\nL\u2019or (Jty Commissioner\n(GROUP 4)\nPAUL J. SHER\nFor City Commissioner\n\u2019(GROUP 5)\nJOE FERNANDEZ\n(Re-Elect)\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 5)\nJAMES A. (Jim)\nFLENNER\nTown Is Helping Injured Grid-man\nPAWNEE. Okla, .p\u2014Residents\nof this small north-central Okla\nj homa town today are backing a\nbig Negro high school football\nplayer's fight to recover from a\nsevere injury.\nAbe Abbington. 18. suffered a\nruptured intestine two weeks ago\nhi a game with Hominy. Okla\nLast week he underwent a five\nhour operation. Since then, six\n\u2022vhite teammates have given blood\nfor transfusions\nThe Pawnee High School girls\nTHE KEY WEST CITIZEN\nTelevision Listings\nCHANNEL 4 TV WTVJ\nMONDAY EVEMXG\n600 Sport\u00ab 9:00 Studio One*\n6.10 Weather 10:00 Innei Sanct.\n6:13 Renick 10 30 Two On Aisle\n6:30 Robin Hood- 11:00 Sews\n7:00 Burns, Allen* 111 ;1O Weather\n7:30 Talent Scouts* 11:15 Sport.\n8:00 D. Thomas* i 11:23 Feature\n8.30 O'Henry i 1.00 Sign OK\nTUESDAY MORMXG\n7.00 Jimmv Dean* 9.00 Garrv Moor*\n7:45 News* 9:30 A Godfrey*\n7:55 News, Weafh 10:30 Strike Rich*\n8.00 Cap K\u2019garoo* 11 00 Hotel Cosmo*\n8:45 News* 11:15 Love of Life*\n8:55 News. Weath. 11:30 Search*\n11:45 Guilt Light*\nPoray Studio\nHOURS:\n10;00 A.M. to 7:00 P.M.\n404 SOUTHARD STREET\nPHONE CY 6-3088\nCHANNEL 5 TV WPTV\nMONDAY EVENING\nR.OO Sports 8:30 Goody\n6: to Naws I 9:00 Suspicioif*\n6:25 Weather i 10:00 Weather\n6:30 Price Ri<ht* 10:05 News\n7:00 Dec. Bride 10:15 Sport*\n7:30 Wells Fargo 10:25 Theater\n00 21* 11.30 Sign Off\nCHANNEL 6 TV HAVANA\nMONDAY EVENING\nB.no Josa Antonio 8:30 Garrido\nAlonno Pinero\n8.36 Ef Programs 8.00 Conflictog\nGravi Humanos\n7.25 El Album 9:32 SiUo Alegr*\nPhillips 10:00 El Rostro del\n7:43 Notlcierb Destine\nCMQ-TV 10:30 Mesa\n8:59 Cascabeles